an></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.21pt; padding-left:4.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The academies programme</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> variously refers to pre-2010 academies and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">following the 2010 Act,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">converter or sponsored a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">cademies; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">it is not easy to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">comment on and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">attribute successes or weaknesses to the programme </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">as a whole</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">requires a more nuanced understanding. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, many of the lessons learnt </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">from successfully developing </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">academies are now being applied across </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">all parts of the school system and so it wo</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">uld be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">misleading to conclude that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">academy status</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> is the only, or even the most effective way of securing such improvement.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> Our comments are based on the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">brea</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">dth of the Church of England's </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">experience in this area </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">comes through us being the largest pr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ovider of academies in the country</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">We have sought to engage positively with the whole programme but are encountering a number of difficulties and challenges, not least because of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">particular </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">responsibil</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ities </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">site trustees have to ensure that any educ</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ation provision on their </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">site is offered in accordance with the terms of the trust. This legal responsibility means that the ‘free market’ approach to sponsorship for other schools cannot simply be applied to Church schools and academies. Instead, the Dioc</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">esan Board of Education’s consent must be sought f</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">or any change to academy stat</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">us; the need and desire for DBE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s to build a strong family of schools and academies does not always seem to be understood in the way the general policy on academies is applied by</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> the DfE.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Looking to the future development of the programme we suggest that a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">more devolved structure is required to enable academies to be properly </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">supported and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">held to account, but we do not feel that a simple regional structure would be the most </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">effective. We suggest that, given the scale of the ch</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">urch’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s provision there should be scope within any developing structures for a solution which is specifically tailored to Church schools and academies to be found.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The Church of England has</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> played a significant role in the provision of education across the country. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">For</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> more than 200 years we have developed our mission to provide excellent education for people of all backgrounds and in all communities. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Throughout that time there have been c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">onstant changes and developments within the education system, but since the 1944 Education Reform Act there has been a clear understanding of the partnership between dioceses (Church of England and Roman Catholic) and Local Authorities as statutory provide</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">rs of education working in what has been called the dual system. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">This is still the framework within which the majority of schools operate, and although there have been rapid recent changes to the way education is organised, which have seen a number of ot</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">her providers enter the education arena, the reality is still that 90% of all primary schools and 40% of secondary schools continue to operate within that statutory framework of the dual system. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">However, the Church of Eng</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">land has engaged with the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> recent </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">significant organisational changes in order to ensure that we continue to develop and improve our education provision as part of our mission to serve the common good, not out of self interest or because we are looking for</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> commercial profit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, but fundamental</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ly because we believe that our schools offer high quality, holistic education which serves children and young people well.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Pre-2010 the focus for academ</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">y development </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">was the secondary sector,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">replacing underperforming schools that were usually situated in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">areas with</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> high levels of deprivation;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> most of our 43 dioceses sponsored or co-sponsored schools in order to bring fresh impetus and innovative leadership to schools which had been attempting to serve the poorest communities for many years. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.88pt; padding-left:3.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The Academies Act of 2010 saw the emphasis shift away from the most difficult and challenging schools towards a model of independence and autonomy for schools that were judged to be good and outstanding, offering them the freedom to make their own decision</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s and be much more in control of their finances and curriculum.  A significant proportion of secondary schools took up this opportunity, but primary schools were much more reticent. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In 2011 the emphasis changed once again</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> with a new focus on underperformance at primary level and a resulting expectation that such schools should be sponsored as academies to enable stronger leadership and governance models to bring about the rapid improvement necessary. However, given the dif</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ferences of scale </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">between</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> primary and secondary schools, it is clear that such transformation can only be sustainable as schools work and collaborate together; dioceses have been seeking to develop structures and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">frameworks that allow schools to flourish, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">support and be supported as an interdependent family of schools, rather than create independent autonomous units.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.67pt; padding-left:0.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">One of our major concerns with the piecemeal way in which the programme has developed is that the resulting landscape</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> is one where the shift </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">from a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ual system operating by statute,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> to one for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">academies which is now a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">contractual arrangement between the Secretary of State and ind</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ividual Academy Trust companies</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, results in confusion and misunderstanding. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The interaction of educational and char</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ity law, some of which dates from the early 19</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> century, and the consequent difficulty in understanding both the history of site ownership and of the various dealings that have been undertaken over a period of time</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> and also the correct procedures that sh</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ould now be undertaken (e.g. in making a site available for an academy)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> means that the whole area of school site ownership and its handling in legislation should be looked at afresh and at least brought together in a coherent piece of new legislation. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">U</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">nder the present system for academies, site trustees are being asked to behave in a contractual relationship as ‘landowner’ without having any resources to carry out this function appropriately. Under the existing statutory relationship it is clear where t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">he responsibility for statutory transfers, costs and warranties lies, and the resources are available to ensure they are dealt with appropriately, but the breakdown of that system and the determination of the EFA and DfE to operate the new system without r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">eally recognising the historic way in which Church academies occupy their site, means that it is becoming m</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ore challenging </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">for charitable trustees to consent to their sites being used in this way.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The complexity of all these developments means it is diffi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">cult to make firm assertions about the academy movement in general. Many aspects of it are to be welcomed, especially the renewed focus on improving education outcomes for the most disadvantaged in society (which is why the Church of England started univer</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">sal education and continues to be our highest priority), but much of the accompanying detail and bureaucracy makes the system feel overly complex and often lacking in transparency.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Data and statistics do not always make clear the distinction between pre-2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">010 academies and current </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">‘sponsored’ or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">‘converter’ academies and there is therefore a great deal of room for misinterpretation of the figures.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The brea</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">dth of the Church of England's </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">experience in this area comes through us being the largest provider of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">academies in the country: 121 of our 221 secondary schools (55%) are now academies and 240 of our 4,443 primary schools (5%). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">We recognise that there is a world of difference between the challenges facing academies born out of schools that serve areas of high deprivation with generations of low educational aspiration, as compared to schools that have enjoyed outstanding leadershi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">p and serve communities where parents are fully engaged and support the vision for education, but we are committed to working for an education system where all prosper and the advantaged help the disadvantaged, the strong support the weak. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">It is within t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">he framework of the above points that we now turn to the specific questions of the Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">As described above, there is a big difference between the pre-2010 academies and more recent ‘converters’ from good and outstanding schools.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">For those early academies there was huge opportunity </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">for independently minded and entrepreneurial leadership to make a dramatic difference from the outset. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In such schools, even holding an assembly could be innovative. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Changing the atmosphere of the school, raising the bar of expectation around discipline </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">or the introduction of a better school uniform brought immediate changes.  Academisation may have been the catalyst for such thinking, but it no longer has a monopoly on it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">For example, in the period from 2006-2010 most of our academies introduced blazer</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s as part of the new school uniform, which seemed innovative and effective, but now most schools (academy or not) have adopted similar policies on uniform. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">These early successful academies did not just transform outcomes for the students who attended the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">m, but they also significantly improved standards in neighbouring schools by proving that it could be done.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The following evidence from one Church of England academy, the David Young Community Academy in Leeds, illustrates experience:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.25pt; padding-left:3.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Attendance at prede</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">cessor schools (both of whom were supported by LA EWOs full-time) was 83%. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">YCA attendance now running at ov</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">er 92% and handled </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">in house</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.25pt; padding-left:3.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">x</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">A*-C 21% in predecessor school 2006, 95% at DYCA</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.69pt; padding-left:4.31pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">x</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">A*-CEM 10% in predecessor school in 2006, 50% at DYCA</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.25pt; padding-left:3.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">NEETs </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">from DYCA now below Leeds average and East Leeds average, yet IMD places 60%+ of students in bottom 5% of population.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.25pt; padding-left:3.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Results</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">from neighbouring school have also risen.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 65.5pt; padding-left:6.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In 2006-7 the principal was criticised for setting too challenging targets by a very sen</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ior LA officer. This would never happen now.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">These early academies definitely changed the way LAs, governing bodies and school leaders thought about the possibilities and potential of schools in the most challenging circumstances. As a consequence, school</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s in the most challenging circumstances no longer have low aspirations for their students, but there is still a huge amount to be done to close the gap. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">However, whilst all of this can be described as a success of the academies programme, it would be mi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">sleading to conclude that this is the only, or even the most effective way of securing such improvement. In order to demonstrate this point, we turn to an example of a school that has achieved outstanding results o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">utside of the academy programme:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">St Peter</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">’s, Ashton under Lyne</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> is a Voluntary Aided Church of England primary school</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In 2011, St Peter’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s was in the 87</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">percentile for all subjects (and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> within that it was in the 100</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">for English). Thanks to the inspirational leadership of its head teacher and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">the support of the Diocese and Local</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> Authority, it is now in the 1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">percentile for progress in all subjects and is to be one of the top 50 high performing schools to be surveyed by Ofsted who recognise its ‘best practice.’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">St Peter’s remarkable achievemen</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">t is in the context of:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">41.5% Eligible for FSM</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">38% White British (20% Pakistani)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">47% First language other than British</span></li></ul></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In order to achieve such step changes,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> schools need the most independently minded, innovative and entrepreneurial lead</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">However, experience suggests that such leaders are not necessarily attracted by the emerging structures and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">risk of choosing to work in an under-performing school is seen as too great, given the repercussions for not being able to turn the school ar</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ound in a very short space of time.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">including working with sponsors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">LAs still have statutory responsibility for place planning, but the creation of a market for the provis</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ion of places requires a much greater level of transparency about the processes involved </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">in commissioning </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">school</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> places</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. Some LAs have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">preferred partners</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> that they have chosen to work with, or commercial companies to whom they have contracted out their s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">chool improvement services, and for such bodies to then win the ’competition’ to provide a required academy without a clear justification or transparency about the reasons for awarding it to them, leads to a lack of trust in the sector.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Similarly, the gov</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ernment has stated that it wishes the decision making to be at a much more local level than is possible when academies are controlled by central government, but our experience is that, even though an LA and local parents would like one solution, the DfE ha</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s imposed another one without any justification for the process. Indeed, in one example the new primary school was awarded to an organisation with no primary experience rather than the LA’s preferred option of the local diocese with its excellent primary p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">artners. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Details of these examples can be provided if required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Given the way in which Church school sites are held, it is essential that any school or academy operating on that site has a clear understanding and ability to run the school as a Church of E</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ngland school, otherwise the trustees would have to give notice to the school to quit its site.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> This is why a necessary and vital step on the journey to become a Church of England academy is seeking the consent of the Diocesan Board of Education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">This bei</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ng so the National Society and the DfE have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">agreed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> a Memorandum of Understanding which sets out the principles on which decisions about academy sponsorship for Church of England schools will be made. This MoU is now well established and enables schools and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> dioceses to have clarity about the choices open to them. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">While t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">his </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">establishes a clear framework nationally, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">we are concerned that there is undue procrastination and too many false options being presented to governing bodies, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">especially </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">when the diocese </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">has already proven itself to be a compet</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ent and effective sponsor. Such</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">issues</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, especially in relation to voluntary controlled schools where the foundation governors are not in the majority and so have to wait for consensus to be achieved, cause </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">unnecessary delay to the process and have a detrimental impact on the education of the children in the school</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">; they</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> need a much quicker solution to be found.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Delays are also often caused by the failure of LAs to have carried out the necessary statutory la</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">nd transfers in the past. We estimate that 1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">000 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">of our </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">school sites have not been transferred properly and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">so </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">having to sort each one out at the time of conversion leads to further delay, complexity and cost. As stated above, a solution which addresses th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">is broader issue and simplifies the process would be highly desirable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">There is also evidence that schools which want to convert into the Diocesan Multi-Academy Trust are being held back by </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">a process which questions the capacity of that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Trust</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, but the pur</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">pose of bringing the schools in to it is intended to create and develop capacity. This </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">impasse results</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> in the schools not being able to convert at all, since the diocese cannot give consent for the schools to join a different trust at the expense of securi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ng the future of its own wider family of Church of England schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">It is clear that there is not enough capacity for the DfE to manage thousands of individual academies from the centre. Reduction in DfE staff at the same time as greater demand for detailed involvement in academies </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">is made of them, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">makes the future expansi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">on of the programme unworkable with</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> the current structure</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. A more devolved solution is needed, but such a solution needs to cater for the complexity of trying to hold together th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">e conflicting methodologies of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">statute and contract, as described above.  A</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> solution which manages the relationship with academies at a local level but does not enable academies and maintained schools to be brought together for strategic purposes, will always lead to confusion and inefficiency.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Such a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">devolved</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> solution also need</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s to fully understand the role of the churches in providing schools and, given the scale of our provision, it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> be preferable to establish a clear structure which enables the specific issues relating to Church schools to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> be dealt with more effectively,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> rather than try and squeeze them in to a general regional approach. The churches have clear and effective structures which enable local diocesan autonomy whilst achieving national coherence, and this would be a more appropriate structure for Church school</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">s and academies to work within.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibil</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In a mixed economy of education provision, there needs to be a locally accountable body which acts as the champion for children, ensuring that they get the very best education p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ossible. It is often assumed that the advantage of the Local Authority carrying out this function is that it provides local democracy and accountability. However, politics can often lead to perverse incentives and solutions. Many schools have been expanded</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, or not expanded, opened or closed, because of how such decisions will play out in the ballot box, not primarily because they will be in the best interest of all children. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The LA will need to continue to have responsibility for strategic place planning across a wider area, but in order to bring real local accountability, much smaller clusters of schools (say </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">30-</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">50 schools) should be enabled to collaborate within tighter geog</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">raphical areas to ensure that there is real recognition of the needs of that community and proper accountability to the parents and children within those schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The expectation in current government thinking is that existing school leaders will be the p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">eople who ensure that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">system runs effectively, but given the pressures on school leaders to drive up performance it seems unlikely that the majority of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> (especially those involved in smaller primary schools where there is a lack of resource to enab</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">le them to carry out this extended role) would be able to play a significant role in this wider collaborative management. Some other structure which draws on the expertise of the head teachers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> whilst removing the burden of further demands, seems necessary</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">. For this to be true collaboration that offers the greatest benefit to a local community, it needs to include maintained schools, academies, Church schools and non-church schools alike, recognising the differences in approach whilst ensuring that all scho</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ols work together for the good of the local community.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">There have already been significant moves in this direction, with the establishment of multi-academy trusts (without which most primary schools are simply unable to convert to academies) and collabora</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">tive partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> or the increasing move towards ‘all-through’ schools where secondary schools form a consortium wi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">th their feeder primary schools </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">but in order to be truly effective, such collaboration needs to cut across the different types of school.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangement</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Many of the national academy chains have proved to be very successful at addressing under</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">performance and bringing about rapid improvement. However, as they expand, they all recognise the need to work in much tighter geographical regions in order to bring maximum impact at a local level.  The Church of England is working in this landscape, not </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">as one national chain, but using the 43 distinct dioceses as the local unit of organisation.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> The advantage of this, whilst </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">having a national organisational structure which ensures consistency of approach and policy decisions relating to the historic nature</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> of Church schools, means that each diocese </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">able to relate to its local community through bishops, clergy and other community structures, in a much more tangible way. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">As described above, it is important that such accountability is built in to the syst</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">em in order to ensure that local needs are met, but we do not believe that this is achieved by simply having one or two parents on a Governing Body. There needs to be much greater connectedness with the whole community of parents</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> (present and prospective) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">but governing b</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">odies have a different function and are responsible for the strate</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">gic direction of the school; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">they need to be more generally accountable to that community rather than have one or two representatives from it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In our report </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A Diocesan Board </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">of Education for the Future</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> we have identified the need for dioceses to form multi-academy trusts as a means of providing high quality leadership and governance across a group of schools, and this seems to be the experience of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> other academy chains as well.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> However, it is essential that such hig</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">h level go</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">vernance does not result in the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> being a distance from</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> or lack of understanding about the school’s specific local context. The use of local advisory committees is a positive way of ensuring this balance is</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> kept.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The fact that only 10% of primary schools have become academies (within the Church of England sector </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">it is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">only 5%) is indicative of the feeling that academy status is not appr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">opriate for individual primary schools</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Since 2010 the Church of England has ta</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ken the view that academy status should be about interdependence, not independence, particularly because the vast majority (4,443) of our schools are primary, and most of those have fewer than 210 pupils. We do not think that a school of this size can achi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">eve the economies of scale that make single academy trust status viable and so we have sought ways to ensure that schools can form MATs together. This was hampered by the insistence that VC and VA schools maintain their predecessor school governance struct</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ures, but we are pleased that a solution has now been found which makes it possible for such a mixed category of schools to form a trust together.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">This interdependence and collaboration is increasingly important as pressures on school budgets increase and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> support from LAs reduces. But it is the interdependence that is ultimately important, not the status of being an academy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">However, the ability to form geographically coherent collaborations and MATs is often hampered by the permissive approach to convers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ion. It is difficult to get an entir</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">e group of governing bodies or h</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ead</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">teachers to agree at the same time that they should voluntarily convert together, with most individual schools preferring to hope that they will keep their own head teacher and their o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">wn Governing Body. But an increasing sense of reality about the future pressures on funding for small schools will make such decisions to form structural collaborations more likely as a means of securing the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">on-going</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> presence of education in rural communit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ies, rather than resort to transporting children miles away from their homes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">As described in the case of St </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Peter’s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">, above, there are many ways of securing lasti</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ng improvement which do not req</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">uire academy status. What </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">we do </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">requ</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ire</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> is confident, competent and professional teach</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ers and leaders who are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> driven by a desire to continually develop and perform </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">better,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> rather than by fear. As such, much greater resource s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ho</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">uld be directed to supporting, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">mentoring and developing school leaders for the future. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">Ensuring that our best and most</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> experienced leaders are able to offer this support, rather than increasingly expecting them to solve other school’s problems, will en</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">able a strong resilient school system to be secured for the future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">The Church of England remains committed to ensuring our schools are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> more effective, more distinctive and more inclusive. We are determined that every child in a Church of England school is in a school that provides a full and rounded education which enables each child to develop character and virtues that will equip them </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">for the rest of their lives. Part of this commitment means that we expect all of our schools to be rated as good or outstanding by Ofsted. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">This determination is not </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">dependent</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> on the academies programme but is as equally applicable to all categories of Chur</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">ch school.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">In seeking to bring about this continued </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">improvement we will work in partnership with </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">government, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">other schools and Local Authorities</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">but the Church, through its local Diocesan Board of Education, is best placed to take the necessary action </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">and implement local strategies that will ensure that the schools and academies it provides are of the highest quality</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">This commitment to excellence in education has meant that we have engaged constructively and proactively with the academies programme. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">However, there are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">a number of issues</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> which cause us to question whethe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">r continued participation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">academies </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">programme which fails to recognise the particular role the Church of England has in relation to its schools</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt"> is in the best interest of those schools and their future. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>